What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset involves information on 113937 loans and their borrowers represented using 81 features. The features are mostly of categorical and numerical types.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The dataset contains a large number of features related to the borrwer themselves including, financial situation, type of loan, history of loans, etc. It would be possible to analyse what features correlate with which loan outcome status.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The main focus will be LoanStatus. This will be used to get completed or overdue loans and determine factors that affect the category's likelihood. The features to be explored will be:

  • LoanStatus: Categories are Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue (with duration)
  • ProsperScore: A custom risk score, 10 is least risk.
  • ListingCategory: The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing
  • EmploymentStatus: The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing
  • EmploymentStatusDuration: The length in months of the employment status at the time the listing was created
  • IsBorrowerHomeowner: Does the borrower have a mortgage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner
  • OpenRevolvingAccounts: Number of open revolving accounts at the time the credit profile was pulled
  • DebtToIncomeRatio: The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled
  • IncomeRange: The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created
  • LoanOriginalAmount: The origination amount of the loan

Misc. Functions¶

  • Bar plot annotation code from here
In [15]:
# For vertical bar graphs
def annotate_vbar(_ax, _format):
    ymin, ymax = plt.ylim()
    plt.ylim(ymin*1.075, ymax*1.075) # To create empty space for the annotation
    for p in _ax.patches:
        _ax.annotate(format(p.get_height(), _format),
                     (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()),
                     ha = 'center', va = 'center',
                     xytext = (0, 9),textcoords = 'offset points')

# For horizontal bar graphs
def annotate_hbar(_ax, _format):
    xmin, xmax = plt.xlim()
    plt.xlim(xmin*1.075, xmax*1.075) # To create empty space for the annotation
    for p in _ax.patches:
        _ax.annotate(format(p.get_width(), _format),
                     (p.get_width(), p.get_y() + p.get_height() / 2.),
                     ha = 'center', va = 'center',
                     xytext = (18, 0),textcoords = 'offset points')
In [16]:
# Orders given series by its value counts
def orderbycount(_series, reverse = False):
    if(reverse):
        return _series.value_counts().index[::-1]
    else:
        return _series.value_counts().index
In [17]:
# returns series showing only top '_cnt' categories and groups the rest into one
def showonly(_cnt, _series):
    tmp = _series.value_counts()
    tmp2 = tmp.head(_cnt)
    if len(tmp) > _cnt:
        tmp2['remaining {0} categories'.format(len(tmp) - _cnt)] = sum(tmp[_cnt:])
    return tmp2

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • Most of the variables showed usual distributions with little abnormalities
  • Most of the variables tended towards a small number of values where most of the frequency was concentrated
  • Variables did not require much transformation, but DebtToIncomeRatio has possible outliers, so zooming was required to clearly illustrate the distribution

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • Most operations done to tidy the data was for properly ordering categories
    • To better illustrate the distribution if the categories are related
  • For DebtToIncomeRatio zooming on the x-axis was required to better illustrate the distribution
    • The maximum value was 10.01 even though the third quartile was 0.32
    • This lead to alot of information to be squeezed into a small portion of the graph

# correlation matrix
correlationmatrix = df_clean.corr()

# Mask to hide upper triangle
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(correlationmatrix, dtype=bool))

f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))
cmap = sns.diverging_palette(230, 20, as_cmap=True)
ax.set_title("Prosper Loan Data Heatmap")
sns.heatmap(correlationmatrix, mask=mask, cmap=cmap, vmax=.3, center=0, annot=True, square=True, linewidths=.5, cbar_kws={"shrink": .75});
Items of Note:¶
  • The features DebtToIncomeRatio and LoanOriginalAmount seem to be important in Prosper's calculation of ProsperScore
    • DebtToIncomeRatio is weakly negatively correlated to ProsperScore (-0.15), meaning that a high DebtToIncomeRatio is more risk
    • LoanOriginalAmount is weakly positively correlated to ProsperScore (0.27), meaning that a high LoanOriginalAmount is less risk
  • ### Loan Status vs Numeric features #### Prosper Score
